{"type":"message","id":"f9b9edef","parentId":"4496d14b","timestamp":"2026-02-17T19:09:19.024Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Evaluating PowerShell Quirks**\n\nI'm currently grappling with the nuances of PowerShell, specifically its `mkdir` command. It seems its behavior diverges from standard `mkdir` implementations, particularly concerning handling multiple path creations. I'm exploring ways to reconcile these differences and identify the most efficient solution.\n\n\n**Addressing File Creation Issues**\n\nI'm presently focused on correcting the file creation procedures. The initial approach for `mkdir` was flawed, so I'm implementing a revised directory structure, considering the differing requirements of PowerShell. I will also be working to rectify an encoding-related issue in `exec_guard.py` along with confirming `stdout` behavior.\n\n\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"exec_1771355352425_88","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"mkdir -Force src/core; mkdir -Force scripts; mkdir -Force logs; mkdir -Force docs"},"thoughtSignature":""},{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Resolving Directory Structures**\n\nI'm now zeroing in on the directory creation issue; it's clear PowerShell's `mkdir` is the culprit. I'm restructuring the creation process to align with PowerShell's requirements and plan to adjust `os_utils.py` accordingly. Also, the `exec_guard.py` script requires refinement due to encoding snags and possible issues with how `stdout` is managed, especially concerning the `write()` call. I will force UTF-8 to ensure proper handling of output.\n\n\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"write_1771355357339_89","name":"write","arguments":{"content":"import os\nimport re\n\ndef get_safe_command(cmd: str) -> str:\n    \"\"\"\n    Translates common shell commands to be safe and compatible with the current OS.\n    Currently focuses on adapting Linux-style commands for Windows PowerShell.\n    \"\"\"\n    if os.name != 'nt':\n        return cmd\n\n    # Basic translation for Windows PowerShell\n    \n    # Replace && with ; (PowerShell treats ; as separator. && works in PS 7+, but ; is safer for general compat)\n    # We replace \" && \" with \" ; \" to avoid breaking strings that just contain &&\n    safe_cmd = cmd.replace(\" && \", \" ; \")\n\n    # Replace rm -rf with Remove-Item -Recurse -Force\n    # Using regex to capture the target is safer, but for this specific requirement:\n    if \"rm -rf \" in safe_cmd:\n        safe_cmd = safe_cmd.replace(\"rm -rf \", \"Remove-Item -Recurse -Force \")\n    elif safe_cmd.strip() == \"rm -rf\":\n        # Handle case where it's just the command (unlikely but possible fragment)\n        safe_cmd = \"Remove-Item -Recurse -Force\"\n    \n    return safe_cmd\n","file_path":"src/core/os_utils.py"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"write_1771355358899_90","name":"write","arguments":{"content":"import sys\nimport subprocess\nimport os\n\ndef run_guarded_command(command):\n    \"\"\"\n    Executes a command, captures output, implements pagination, and logs full output.\n    \"\"\"\n    # Ensure logs directory exists\n    os.makedirs(\"logs\", exist_ok=True)\n    log_file = \"logs/last_exec.log\"\n\n    try:\n        # Run command and capture output\n        # Use shell=True for flexibility.\n        # Force encoding to utf-8 to avoid charmap errors on Windows, or use errors='replace'\n        # Env vars might be needed for encoding\n        env = os.environ.copy()\n        env[\"PYTHONIOENCODING\"] = \"utf-8\"\n        \n        result = subprocess.run(\n            command, \n            shell=True, \n            capture_output=True, \n            text=True, \n            encoding='utf-8', \n            errors='replace',\n            env=env\n        )\n        \n        stdout = result.stdout if result.stdout else \"\"\n        stderr = result.stderr if result.stderr else \"\"\n        \n        full_output = stdout\n        if stderr:\n            full_output += \"\\n[STDERR]\\n\" + stderr\n\n        # Log full output\n        with open(log_file, \"w\", encoding=\"utf-8\") as f:\n            f.write(full_output)\n\n        lines = stdout.splitlines()\n        line_count = len(lines)\n        \n        # Pagination Logic\n        if line_count > 20:\n            head = lines[:10]\n            tail = lines[-10:]\n            \n            print(\"\\n\".join(head))\n            print(f\"\\n... [{line_count - 20} lines hidden. See {log_file}] ...\\n\")\n            print(\"\\n\".join(tail))\n        else:\n            print(stdout)\n            \n        if stderr:\n            print(\"[STDERR]\", stderr)\n\n    except Exception as e:\n        print(f\"Error executing command: {e}\")\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    if len(sys.argv) < 2:\n        print(\"Usage: python exec_guard.py <command>\")\n    else:\n        # Reconstruct command from args\n        cmd = \" \".join(sys.argv[1:])\n        \n        # Import os_utils to sanitize/translate\n        try:\n            # Add src to path\n            current_dir = os.path.dirname(os.path.abspath(__file__))\n            src_path = os.path.abspath(os.path.join(current_dir, \"../src\"))\n            sys.path.append(src_path)\n            \n            from core.os_utils import get_safe_command\n            cmd = get_safe_command(cmd)\n            # print(f\"DEBUG: Executing safe command: {cmd}\") \n        except ImportError:\n            print(\"Warning: Could not import os_utils. Running raw command.\")\n            \n        run_guarded_command(cmd)\n","file_path":"scripts/exec_guard.py"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"write_1771355359020_91","name":"write","arguments":{"content":"# ARCHITECTURE V5\n\nThis is a dummy file to test the pagination logic.\nIt needs to have more than 20 lines to trigger the guard.\n\nLine 04\nLine 05\nLine 06\nLine 07\nLine 08\nLine 09\nLine 10\nLine 11\nLine 12\nLine 13\nLine 14\nLine 15\nLine 16\nLine 17\nLine 18\nLine 19\nLine 20\nLine 21 - Hidden\nLine 22